🧠 Terraform Modules – Complete Notes (VPC → EC2 Example)
1. Problem Statement (What are we solving?)

You have:

A VPC module → creates VPC + subnets
An EC2 module → creates EC2 instances

👉 Now you want:

“While creating EC2, how do I use the VPC ID and Subnet IDs created in another module?”

2. Core Concept (VERY IMPORTANT)

Terraform modules do NOT directly access each other.

✔️ Instead, they communicate like this:

Module A (VPC)
   ↓ (outputs)
Root Module
   ↓ (inputs)
Module B (EC2)

👉 Think of it like:

VPC module returns values (outputs)
Root module passes those values
EC2 module receives them as inputs
3. Step-by-Step Implementation
🔹 Step 1: Create VPC Module
📁 modules/vpc/variables.tf
variable "vpc_cidr" {
  type = string
}

variable "subnet_cidrs" {
  type = list(string)
}

👉 These are inputs to the VPC module.

📁 modules/vpc/main.tf
resource "aws_vpc" "this" {
  cidr_block = var.vpc_cidr
}

resource "aws_subnet" "this" {
  count      = length(var.subnet_cidrs)
  vpc_id     = aws_vpc.this.id
  cidr_block = var.subnet_cidrs[count.index]
}

👉 Here:

var.vpc_cidr → comes from root module
aws_vpc.this.id → generated after creation
📁 modules/vpc/outputs.tf ✅ IMPORTANT
output "vpc_id" {
  value = aws_vpc.this.id
}

output "subnet_ids" {
  value = aws_subnet.this[*].id
}

👉 This is the MOST IMPORTANT PART

Without outputs ❌ → other modules cannot use this data
With outputs ✅ → data becomes accessible

🔹 Step 2: Create EC2 Module
📁 modules/ec2/variables.tf
variable "vpc_id" {
  type = string
}

variable "subnet_ids" {
  type = list(string)
}

👉 These are inputs expected from outside

📁 modules/ec2/main.tf
resource "aws_instance" "example" {
  ami           = "ami-xxxxxxxx"
  instance_type = "t2.micro"

  subnet_id = var.subnet_ids[0]  # using first subnet
}

👉 Key idea:

EC2 module does NOT know how VPC was created

It just uses:

var.vpc_id
var.subnet_ids
🔹 Step 3: Root Module (Glue Everything Together)
📁 main.tf (ROOT MODULE)
provider "aws" {
  region = "us-east-1"
}
👉 Call VPC Module
module "vpc" {
  source = "./modules/vpc"

  vpc_cidr     = "10.0.0.0/16"
  subnet_cidrs = ["10.0.1.0/24", "10.0.2.0/24"]
}
👉 Call EC2 Module (IMPORTANT PART)
module "ec2" {
  source = "./modules/ec2"

  vpc_id     = module.vpc.vpc_id
  subnet_ids = module.vpc.subnet_ids
}
🚨 THIS LINE IS THE MAGIC
vpc_id = module.vpc.vpc_id

👉 Breakdown:

module.vpc → refers to VPC module
.vpc_id → refers to output from that module
4. Data Flow Diagram
[VPC Module]
   ├── creates VPC
   ├── creates subnets
   └── outputs:
        ├── vpc_id
        └── subnet_ids
             ↓
[Root Module]
             ↓
[EC2 Module]
   ├── receives vpc_id
   ├── receives subnet_ids
   └── creates EC2
5. Super Important Rules (Memorize This)
✅ Rule 1: Modules NEVER directly talk

❌ Wrong:

module.ec2 → access module.vpc directly

✅ Correct:

module.vpc → output → root → input → module.ec2
✅ Rule 2: Outputs are required to share data

If you don’t define:

output "vpc_id"

👉 You CANNOT access it.

✅ Rule 3: Use module.<name>.<output>
module.vpc.vpc_id
module.vpc.subnet_ids
✅ Rule 4: EC2 module must declare variables

If you don’t declare:

variable "vpc_id"

👉 Terraform will throw error ❌

6. Advanced: Create EC2 in ALL Subnets

Instead of one EC2:

subnet_id = var.subnet_ids[0]

👉 Create multiple EC2s:

resource "aws_instance" "example" {
  for_each = toset(var.subnet_ids)

  ami           = "ami-xxxxxxxx"
  instance_type = "t2.micro"
  subnet_id     = each.value
}
7. Real-World Analogy (Easy to Remember)

Think like this:

VPC module = Factory
Outputs = Products
Root module = Delivery guy
EC2 module = Customer

Factory → gives product → delivery → gives to customer

8. Common Mistakes ❌
❌ Mistake 1:

Trying to access like:

module.ec2.vpc_id = module.vpc.aws_vpc.this.id

👉 WRONG (cannot access internal resources)

❌ Mistake 2:

Forgetting outputs

❌ Mistake 3:

Not passing variables to EC2 module

9. Final Summary (One Look Revision)

✔️ VPC module:

Creates resources
Exports using output

✔️ Root module:

Connects modules

✔️ EC2 module:

Receives inputs using variable

✔️ Data flow:

module.vpc.output → module.ec2.input
